Quiet read-outside-sandbox warnings

Upstream recently added warnings when you try to read a file outside the
sandbox.  They're nice, but very noisy for us since apparently we have a lot of
code that does that.  (My guess is it's mostly just imports checking various
places on PYTHONPATH that they can't see.)  So I turned the warnings down a bit
for us, so they'll be off by default.  (Note that I couldn't actually figure
out how to show them -- neither `--log_level` nor `--dev_appserver_log_level`
seemed to work, and I gave up on shaving that yak.  Hopefully if we do want
them we can figure out how at that point.)

Ignore IPv6 zone ID in inet_pton.

Summary:
`fe80::1%lo0` is a valid IPv6 address and zone ID, however, the dev
server previously errored if it encountered this address.

It now ignores the scope, which doesn't seem ideal, but is much better
than conistently erroring.

Before this change, my dev server was consistently erroring whenever,
I hit various endpoints, including the problem attempt endpoint. I
think it's due to some pecularities in how my network is configured,
but I haven't narrowed it down.

This change is letting me move forward with my other work in the short
term. If we don't want to land this change onto the Frankenserver I'm
happy to use this locally in the short term and then debug my network
configuration once I have time, to prevent this sort of address from
ever making it to this level.

```

import google.appengine.api.remote_socket._remote_socket_addr as _remote_socket_addr

without_scope = _remote_socket_addr.inet_pton(_remote_socket_addr.AF_INET6, "fe80::1")
```

Stop dev_appserver from using 100% CPU with fsevents_file_watcher

Summary:
https://app.asana.com/0/27216215224639/52930358597729

It looks like the `changes` spec was changed to have a long polling behavior
with the GAE upgrade: it takes a `timeout_ms` and is expected to block until
either any files have changed or the timeout expires. Instead, we were always
returning the set of changes immediately, even if it was empty, so the
dev_appserver code was calling it continuously in a loop. This commit changes
the implementation so `_fsevents_callback` notifies an event so `changes`
returns when the changes actually happen (or after the timeout).

exclude vim's crazy permission probes from reload

Summary:
On file save, vim checks for write permission to the directory.
It does this by trying to create an empty file.
Instead of being called something sensible like `.vim_permission_test`,
the file is called `4913`.
If this file is taken, it's called `5036`, then `5159`, etc.
(increasing in increments of `123`).
These magic numbers are hardcoded into vim.
See the source [here](https://github.com/jamessan/vim/blob/5bfa4c85b0d82c8830ac391cc73ffbe8f9e6feb0/src/fileio.c#L3704),
or a discussion [here](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!msg/vim_dev/sppdpElxY44/qdYb2g_xI_oJ).

This patch prevents unnecessary reloads by excluding those files.

 3. Apply patch.

Have the file-watchers ignore files that are not in skip-files.

Summary:
The motivation is that if a file is in an app.yaml's skip_files, then
it is not accessible to the dev-appserver, and thus we don't care if
it changes or not.

This allows applications to store files such as the datastore inside
the app directory, without having to worry about constant reloads as a
result.  It also opens the door -- if we wanted to -- of lifting the
assumption that we never need to watch dot-directories in
watcher_common.py, and instead explicitly skip the dot-directories
that the user puts in skip_files.

As part of this change, I removed the _IMMUTABLE_PROPERTIES part of
ModuleConfiguration.  It didn't work well with skip-files reloading,
and I believe that's obsolete these days in any case, since we always
spin up a new instance when the yaml files change.

The implementation mostly involves passing around the skip-files RE to
the watchers.  We have to do a little work on some watchers to get the
filenames relative to application-root, since the filenames in the
skip-files RE are all taken to be relative to the application-root.

Summary:
Appengine issue #13477 notes that some of the google apis certificates expired

Differential Revision: https://phabricator.khanacademy.org/D33354

Pass down dev appserver restart time to python runtime

Summary:
We'd like to have caches that depend on the last `dev_appserver` restart time,
as a simulation of depending on the App Engine version in prod.  (For example,
we want to have caches that are expired on a new App Engine version expire
whenever the dev server restarts.)  `dev_appserver`'s own version is set on
first start, so that won't change when we want it to, and `dev_appserver` may
start multiple instances, so doing something in our code at import-time will
change too often.  So we need to add our own.

Figuring out the right place to do this was a little tricky, but it seemed like
there was no way to do it generally for all runtimes, since we need to hook
into instance creation to edit the runtime config and add the environment
variable.  So we do it in the python runtime, and just have it log the last
time it restarted (i.e. either startup or on file-change).  Then we can just
inject it into the runtime config's environment.

Test Plan:
Added an import-time print statement in our code (`ka_globals.py`) to print
`os.environ['DEV_APPSERVER_LAST_RESTART_TIME']`.  Started a dev server (with
`--max_module_instances=10` to make sure it would load a bunch of new
instances), and saw it print the same value several times, even after loading
some pages.  Touched a file, and saw it print the same new value several times.
Restarted the dev server with `--automatic_restarts 0`, and saw it print the
same value several times, and not change even after touching some files and
loading some pages.

Have the file-watchers ignore files that are not in skip-files.

Summary:
The motivation is that if a file is in an app.yaml's skip_files, then
it is not accessible to the dev-appserver, and thus we don't care if
it changes or not.

the app directory, without having to worry about constant reloads as a
result.  It also opens the door -- if we wanted to -- of lifting the
assumption that we never need to watch dot-directories in
watcher_common.py, and instead explicitly skip the dot-directories
that the user puts in skip_files.

As part of this change, I removed the _IMMUTABLE_PROPERTIES part of
ModuleConfiguration.  It didn't work well with skip-files reloading,
and I believe that's obsolete these days in any case, since we always
spin up a new instance when the yaml files change.

The implementation mostly involves passing around the skip-files RE to
the watchers.  We have to do a little work on some watchers to get the
filenames relative to application-root, since the filenames in the
skip-files RE are all taken to be relative to the application-root.

Stop dev_appserver from using 100% CPU with fsevents_file_watcher

Summary:
https://app.asana.com/0/27216215224639/52930358597729

It looks like the `changes` spec was changed to have a long polling behavior
with the GAE upgrade: it takes a `timeout_ms` and is expected to block until
either any files have changed or the timeout expires. Instead, we were always
returning the set of changes immediately, even if it was empty, so the
dev_appserver code was calling it continuously in a loop. This commit changes
the implementation so `_fsevents_callback` notifies an event so `changes`
returns when the changes actually happen (or after the timeout).

Have the file-watchers ignore files that are not in skip-files.

Summary:
The motivation is that if a file is in an app.yaml's skip_files, then
it is not accessible to the dev-appserver, and thus we don't care if
it changes or not.

This allows applications to store files such as the datastore inside
the app directory, without having to worry about constant reloads as a
result.  It also opens the door -- if we wanted to -- of lifting the
assumption that we never need to watch dot-directories in
watcher_common.py, and instead explicitly skip the dot-directories
that the user puts in skip_files.

As part of this change, I removed the _IMMUTABLE_PROPERTIES part of
ModuleConfiguration.  It didn't work well with skip-files reloading,
and I believe that's obsolete these days in any case, since we always
spin up a new instance when the yaml files change.

The implementation mostly involves passing around the skip-files RE to
the watchers.  We have to do a little work on some watchers to get the
filenames relative to application-root, since the filenames in the
skip-files RE are all taken to be relative to the application-root.

I suggest cloning the repo and running `git log --author="@khanacademy.org"` to see a full list of the changes made by Khan Academy. The commit history isn't as clean as it could be, but at a high level we've:
- improved performance by making file-watching more efficient
- improved IPv6 support
- added a hook for installing a custom logging handler

We're also working on getting some of these patches accepted into the upstream SDK codebase.

## Looking at the Khan forks of these repos, I see that they have changes like this:

## https://github.com/Khan/pyobjc-framework-Cocoa/commit/784c9a2f8b71d67566e4d8f74d11dae0a2a6dac5

I don't know anything about pyobjc, and unfortunately the person who made those forks is no longer at Khan.  Do you know if they have been obsoleted by the latest pyobjs's?  I don't want us to lose those setuptools fixes if they're still a problem.

I'm afraid we've never done any work in Go, so it's totally possible that our fixes are incomplete for that language.

I'm afraid we can't offer much help here -- but if you figure out what to fix, we're glad to accept patches!

Looked into the upstream code and found that they just check the return value and split it.

``` python
# http_runtime.py:328
port = self._process.stdout.readline()
if '\t' in port:  # Split out the host if present.
  host, port = port.split('\t', 1)
```

Maybe we could just do the same?
(Oops, I guess they're pull-requests in github-land.)

Ah, thank you for the code, that helps clarify things for me.  I hadn't realized this was in the python code and not some go-specific code.

It seems like if this is what exists upstream, the real problem is we haven't been keeping frankenserver up to date with the the upstream releases.  I think the right fix would be to just do that.  (Right now we're against 1.9.25.)  I'll see if I can carve out some time this week.
OK, I just pushed a new 1.9.36 branch.  I haven't updated master yet since I haven't done a lot of testing, but try out the new branch and see if it fixes things for you!
The port issue is fixed, and haven't seen other things broken. Thanks!

Wow, time flies.  The project is still active, but we only do the work to update it ourselves when Khan Academy needs to update the SDK, which hasn't been for a while.  We'll do it when we have a chance; it's just a matter of finding time to test the new SDK to make sure it doesn't break anything for us.

Are you having issues with Sierra? I think support for that os upgrade was
added recently.

Good news! -- looking at 1.9.49, it looks like dev_appserver now includes most of the functionality from the frankenserver.  In particular, I see that the file-watcher now respects skip_files.  It also has all the IPv6 patches (with one exception which probably came after they did the mege).

There are a few minor things that frankenserver has that are not in mainline yet, including a resurrection of the fsevents file watcher, and improved pypy support.  But those are minor enough that I don't think there's much reason to recommend the frankenserver over stock appengine sdk anymore.
